Revision history for App-Baphomet

0.0.1	2026-07-12
        - Initial release. Log watcher for Ereshkigal... tails logs, parses
          syslog lines, matches them against YAML rules, and consigns
          offending IPs to Kur via the Ereshkigal manager socket.
        - 47 more rules ported from fail2ban, closing the filter library to
          essentially everything that is a regexp over a log line... more
          syslog daemons, a large raw batch of own-format app and webmail
          logs, more web rules, and slapd via keyed correlation. 135 rules
          shipped now.
        - Visibility commands matching what fail2ban shows... baphomet
          accused lists the IPs being counted but not yet consigned, per
          IP the live hit count and first/last hit epochs, via a new
          accused action on the galla and manager sockets. baphomet
          consigned asks Ereshkigal who Kur holds for the kurs this
          Baphomet feeds, expanding fan_out gates to their members and
          marking bans still pending delivery, with --ip answering which
          kurs hold a address. baphomet ledger reads the consignment
          history... when, which kur, which IP, by which rule and watcher,
          filterable by kur, IP, --since, and --tail.
        - The shared consignment ledger is now chiseled on every
          consignment, recidive or no, and carries rule and watcher
          columns. Retention is bounded by the new ledger_keep setting,
          30 days by default, 0 meaning forever, never pruning inside the
          recidive window.
        - Stats now break down per watcher and per rule alongside the
          galla-wide totals, and persist across restarts via a new stats
          tablet... totals mean since first loosing, not since the last
          respawn.
        - A optional Neti gate on the manager socket, the enable_auth unix
          ownership auth challenge gated by authed_users and authed_groups,
          matching Ereshkigal. socket_mode is now validated at load, and
          socket_group/socket_mode gate the manager socket as before.
        - A internal config field, global and per kur, marking your own
          hosts, and a ban_not_internal rule option consigning the end of
          a flow that is not internal. internal defaults to the ignore
          IPs. All the Suricata rules use it, so the offender is picked as
          the external end whether it is the src or the dest... the flow
          direction depends on where the alert fired.
        - json/suricata-blocked, consigning sources Suricata itself chose
          to block, per eve.json alert.action == "blocked".
        - A rule per Suricata classification class,
          json/suricata-<classtype>, gating on alert.category and
          consigning src_ip, so eve.json can be acted on class by class.
          43 of them, from Suricata's own classification.config.
        - An EVE event log, a Suricata-shaped NDJSON record of what the
          gallas do... found and consign events with eve_type baphomet,
          the raw and parsed line, the found data, a count, and the rule
          minus its tests. Path set by default, written only when
          eve_enable is on. See docs/eve.md.
        - A ignore_ips list, global and per kur, of addresses and CIDRs
          never consigned no matter what the rules say.
        - Each galla persists its state to tablets under tablet_base_dir,
          /var/db/baphomet by default... counters, pending bans,
          correlation context, and log positions, checkpointed and
          restored, so a restart or crash does not forget an attacker
          mid-way and lines written while down are still read.
        - Native systemd journal support... a watcher takes a journal of
          journalctl matches instead of a log, followed via journalctl -o
          json, cursor persisted across restarts. The syslog rules apply
          to it unchanged.
        - Repeat offender escalation via the recidive table... every
          consignment is recorded to a shared ledger and a IP consigned
          too many times across all kurs is dragged through a further gate
          to the recidive kur.
        - A migration guide for people coming from fail2ban, docs/fail2ban.md.
        - A watcher's log may be a array of files and entries may be
          globs, re-expanded every ten seconds while running, so new
          matches, like a freshly created jail, get picked up live.
        - Multiline support via keyed correlation... capture_regexp
          entries harvest context under a key, keyed message_regexp
          entries resolve through it or defer awaiting it, either order,
          TTL bounded and per watcher. Rule tests may be sequences via
          messages. Ships raw/mongodb-auth-legacy and completes
          sendmail-reject's No such user pair.
        - The json parser handles generic JSON application logs, whatever
          the schema, flattening nesting into dotted field paths matched
          by rules of the json type... field gates, per-field match and
          ignore regexps with tokens, and ban_var resolving either a
          capture or a field path. Ships json/mongodb-auth (the modern
          structured format), json/caddy-botsearch, and json/suricata,
          and a journalctl -o json example in the docs.
        - The raw parser is the no-op escape hatch, the whole line as the
          message, matched by rules of the raw type... syslog rules minus
          the daemon gate. Never format-sniffed, only explicitly
          configured. Ships raw/mysqld-auth, raw/exim, and raw/3proxy.
        - The apache_error and nginx_error parsers handle the web server
          error logs, matched by rules of the http_error type... level and
          module gates plus message regexps, banning the parsed client.
          nginx structured pairs are peeled into fields, rightmost wins
          against injection. Rules may set test_parser to default the
          parser for all their embedded tests.
        - The http_access parser handles common and combined HTTP access
          logs, matched by rules of the new http type... gates on status
          and method plus per-field match/ignore regexps, banning the
          client field. Ships http/badbots and http/botsearch. Rule types
          and parsers are cross-checked at start.
        - The syslog parser handles RFC 3164, RFC 5424, and the JSON
          output of syslog-ng (also available on its own as json_syslog),
          sniffed per line, and is the default when a watcher does not
          name a parser. Parsed lines carry a format key saying which
          won. The syslog rules apply to JSON logs unchanged.
        - Rules may carry ignore_regexp entries, the fail2ban ignoreregex
          equivalent, and a watcher's rule may be a array of rules checked
          first-match-wins, for logs carrying several daemons.
        - Licensed GPL-2.0-or-later, matching fail2ban, which the shipped
          rules are derived from.
        - Ships 25 syslog rules translated from the fail2ban filters, each
          carrying tests mined from the fail2ban test log corpus. See
          docs/rules-catalog.md.
